their reintegration.

00:09:34.550 --> 00:09:37.400
And so, this afternoon, we'll
be looking at the reintegration

00:09:37.400 --> 00:09:41.180
of refugees in post-conflict
Liberia specifically,

00:09:41.180 --> 00:09:48.210
but I will focus my talk on the
local and global intersections

00:09:48.210 --> 00:09:53.970
in the ways these refugees forage
home in the Liberian context.

00:09:57.040 --> 00:10:02.530
My paper is based on qualitative
research that I carried in

00:10:02.530 --> 00:10:07.570
and on Liberia between
2006 and 2012,

00:10:07.570 --> 00:10:12.850
in which I employed a
triangulation of methods,

00:10:12.850 --> 00:10:17.880
in-depth interviews were
conducted with 100 refugee women,

00:10:17.880 --> 00:10:22.040
government officials, staff of
international and local agencies,

00:10:22.040 --> 00:10:26.000
community leaders, and other
members of civil society.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:27.300
And these were supplemented

00:10:27.300 --> 00:10:31.850
with non-participant observation
and documentary review.

00:10:31.850 --> 00:10:36.300
I visited five of Liberia's
15 counties to collect data

00:10:36.300 --> 00:10:42.400
for my research and four of these
five counties I visited were the

00:10:42.400 --> 00:10:46.330 position:56%
areas of highest return of refugees.

00:10:46.330 --> 00:10:49.630
Participants were located
through snowballing and they came

00:10:49.630 --> 00:10:53.570
from various backgrounds
and various experiences.

00:10:53.570 --> 00:10:57.480
I collected documents not
just from Liberia but also

00:10:57.480 --> 00:11:01.510
from Geneva during my
post-doctoral time there.

00:11:01.510 --> 00:11:07.440
And I was able to also do some
intersubjective validation

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:12.370
of my data by speaking with
refugee expats, not just in Liberia

00:11:12.370 --> 00:11:15.020
and outside Liberia but in Geneva.

00:11:15.020 --> 00:11:16.320
The UN [inaudible] --

00:11:16.320 --> 00:11:18.430
at the headquarters of the
United Nations High Commission

00:11:18.430 --> 00:11:21.000
for Refugees Office there.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:22.960
So, this is the basis for some

00:11:22.960 --> 00:11:25.490
of the statements I'll
be making this afternoon.

00:11:25.490 --> 00:11:28.590
Let me also quickly say
that my analysis is informed

00:11:28.590 --> 00:11:32.960
by a constructivist view of
international politics relying

00:11:32.960 --> 00:11:37.300 position:56%
on Alexander Wendt's critique of the
so called structure agents problem

00:11:37.300 --> 00:11:41.110
in international relations by
which international anarchy

00:11:41.110 --> 00:11:44.730
and structure are deemed to
be the major determinants

00:11:44.730 --> 00:11:47.730
of international politics
instead, of course,

00:11:47.730 --> 00:11:52.690
Wendt posits that this system is
one in which various actors --

00:11:52.690 --> 00:11:54.560
which we will call agents here --

00:11:54.560 --> 00:11:58.110
play significant roles
in determining structure

00:11:58.110 --> 00:12:01.860
and are themselves in turn,
modified by structure.

00:12:04.140 --> 00:12:08.470
This is important for
my own analysis here

00:12:08.470 --> 00:12:14.640
because it helps me recognize
that there are various --

00:12:14.640 --> 00:12:16.730
there is in existence
various actors --

00:12:16.730 --> 00:12:20.210
from the local to the global
operator within the domain

00:12:20.210 --> 00:12:22.360
of post-conflict reintegration.

00:12:22.360 --> 00:12:24.070
And this makes it possible
for also --

00:12:24.070 --> 00:12:28.890
acknowledge also, the roles of
women in their reintegration

00:12:28.890 --> 00:12:30.830
because their narratives
are often buried

00:12:30.830 --> 00:12:32.790
in the masculinist interpretation

00:12:32.790 --> 00:12:36.050
of international processes
such as this one.

00:12:36.050 --> 00:12:37.760
This framework also
makes it possible

00:12:37.760 --> 00:12:43.040 position:56%
to admit the constraining conditions
which international structure places

00:12:43.040 --> 00:12:46.060
on the activities of the various
agents we'll be mentioning

00:12:46.060 --> 00:12:47.360
in this paper.

00:12:47.360 --> 00:12:49.970
But at the same time, it
brings to relief the ways

00:12:49.970 --> 00:12:53.780
in which these agents
and actors contracts

00:12:53.780 --> 00:12:56.810
or forge their desired outcomes.

00:12:56.810 --> 00:13:01.070
In this case, the idea
of home in Liberia --

00:13:01.070 --> 00:13:05.360
whether consciously
or unconsciously.

00:13:05.360 --> 00:13:11.540 position:56%
I will not bore you with definitions
because we know who refugees are.

00:13:11.540 --> 00:13:12.840
They're eligible basically

00:13:12.840 --> 00:13:16.180
for international protection
under international law.

00:13:16.180 --> 00:13:19.860
And this is because national
protection has failed them.

00:13:19.860 --> 00:13:24.580
And one of the responsibilities
of the international community

00:13:24.580 --> 00:13:30.420
to refugees is to find durable
solutions to their problems.

00:13:30.420 --> 00:13:35.240
And the three solutions that have
been applied over the decades

00:13:35.240 --> 00:13:39.520
that the international
refugee has evolved, of course,

00:13:39.520 --> 00:13:43.570
are repatriation -- that is
return of refugees to the country

00:13:43.570 --> 00:13:48.460
of origin; integration
which involves helping them

00:13:48.460 --> 00:13:52.210
to acquire a new citizenship
in the country of asylum;

00:13:52.210 --> 00:13:54.540
and resettlement with
a third country.

00:13:54.540 --> 00:14:00.680 position:56%
My focus is on repatriation and
voluntary repatriation has become --

00:14:00.680 --> 00:14:04.610
in quotes -- "The most desirable
solution for refugee problems"

00:14:04.610 --> 00:14:06.660
and has been promoted vigorously

00:14:06.660 --> 00:14:09.190
by the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees -- UNHCR.

00:14:09.190 --> 00:14:13.400
And, in fact, the 1990s
were described

00:14:13.400 --> 00:14:15.570
as the decade of repatriation.

00:14:15.570 --> 00:14:19.320
The 2000s were referred
to the new era of return.

00:14:19.320 --> 00:14:22.510
And so, repatriation -- in fact,

00:14:22.510 --> 00:14:26.250
repatriation has become the
buzz word in the last two,

00:14:26.250 --> 00:14:30.810
three decades in refugee
and states practice.

00:14:30.810 --> 00:14:36.160 position:56%
Reintegration is supposed to proceed
concomitantly or after repatriation

00:14:36.160 --> 00:14:39.520 position:56%
and it is a process that is expected
to result in the disappearance

00:14:39.520 --> 00:14:42.110
of differences in legal
rights and duties

00:14:42.110 --> 00:14:45.470
between returnees and
their compatriots.

00:14:48.200 --> 00:14:50.940
In this paper, I am not --

00:14:53.060 --> 00:14:57.790
I am going to focus on the idea
of home, like I said earlier,

00:14:57.790 --> 00:15:01.460
because it's been noted that
one of the chief incentives

00:15:01.460 --> 00:15:04.850
for refugees return to
the country of origin is

00:15:04.850 --> 00:15:09.200
to recover a sense
of feeling at home.

00:15:09.200 --> 00:15:13.840
I have taken the task of home to
task because of the home to task

00:15:13.840 --> 00:15:17.170
in one of my previous papers
where I argued that the illusion

00:15:17.170 --> 00:15:23.600
of home leads to a partial illusion
of peace among returnee women.

00:15:23.600 --> 00:15:25.010
And, therefore, because of

00:15:25.010 --> 00:15:29.710
that return may not be
sustainable in certain instances.

00:15:29.710 --> 00:15:32.780
Today, the questions that
I will be looking at relate

00:15:32.780 --> 00:15:37.730
to how do Liberian refugees
returning from exile

00:15:37.730 --> 00:15:40.810 position:56%
from various west African
countries encounter the country they

00:15:40.810 --> 00:15:42.110
return to.

00:15:42.110 --> 00:15:46.230
In what ways do these returnees --
as members of various communities

00:15:46.230 --> 00:15:51.830
and localities -- invent, shape,
and forage a home for themselves

00:15:51.830 --> 00:15:54.740 position:56%
to enable sustainable reintegration?

00:15:54.740 --> 00:15:58.900
What complimentary rules do local
and international agencies bear

00:15:58.900 --> 00:16:02.000
in either particularistic
of global mandates play

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.540
in these processes
with what outcomes?

00:16:04.540 --> 00:16:09.530 position:56%
And I'm going to argue that refugees
and returnees are not merely victims

00:16:09.530 --> 00:16:14.370
of circumstances nor mere
wards of the national

00:16:14.370 --> 00:16:16.430
and international system.

00:16:16.430 --> 00:16:18.950
Rather they are veritable
agents in constructing

00:16:18.950 --> 00:16:21.280
or forging the home they return to.

00:16:21.280 --> 00:16:24.820 position:56%
We further contain here that the
returnees' perception of the country

00:16:24.820 --> 00:16:30.010
of origin as home, as well as their
steady progress towards the touted

00:16:30.010 --> 00:16:33.230
ideal of home, is significantly
shaped

00:16:33.230 --> 00:16:37.460
by the intersecting activities
of various local, national,

00:16:37.460 --> 00:16:40.970
and international agencies
and [inaudible].

00:16:43.530 --> 00:16:45.830
And so, I am going to --

00:16:47.410 --> 00:16:50.860
In this presentation,
look at these --

00:16:50.860 --> 00:16:52.760
I will begin by provided
international

00:16:52.760 --> 00:16:56.650
and specific Liberian context
and then look at the actuals

00:16:56.650 --> 00:17:00.200
that are involved in this process
of forging or shaping home,

00:17:00.200 --> 00:17:02.920
as well as the points of
intersection between the local

00:17:02.920 --> 00:17:08.430
and the international agencies
and actors in the Liberian case.

00:17:08.430 --> 00:17:13.520
And then conclude with the
statements on what these means

00:17:13.520 --> 00:17:16.880
for the process of forging home.

00:17:17.970 --> 00:17:23.610
Within the global context
between 1991 and 1996,

00:17:23.610 --> 00:17:25.610
repatriation numbers
increased globally.

00:17:25.610 --> 00:17:29.640
Over one million refugees
returned to Ethiopia and Eritrea.

00:17:29.640 --> 00:17:33.100
About 1.7 million Mozambican
refugees returned

00:17:33.100 --> 00:17:34.860
from several neighboring countries.

00:17:34.860 --> 00:17:38.120
More than 2.7 million
Afghans returned from Pakistan

00:17:38.120 --> 00:17:40.660
and Iraq and so on and so forth.

00:17:40.660 --> 00:17:44.320
However, the trend
turned by the mid-2000s.

00:17:44.320 --> 00:17:48.070
official figures from country of
asylum and origin data indicate

00:17:48.070 --> 00:17:54.440
that there has been a decline in
repatriation worldwide by 2014.

00:17:54.440 --> 00:17:57.970
Repatriation was reported
to be at a 30-year low.

00:18:01.070 --> 00:18:10.080
The lowest since 1983 was
recorded at just 126,800 refugees.

00:18:10.080 --> 00:18:13.950
Which was, again, significantly
lower than the year before that.

00:18:13.950 --> 00:18:16.140
These figures are from the UNHCR.

00:18:16.140 --> 00:18:20.310
Significantly, however, of
the eight countries accounted

00:18:20.310 --> 00:18:23.970
for 95% of returns in 2015.

00:18:23.970 --> 00:18:27.690
Six of these countries
are African countries.

00:18:27.690 --> 00:18:29.780
And so, the fate of
these refugees returning

00:18:29.780 --> 00:18:34.340
to sometimes unstable transitional
context is an important subject

00:18:34.340 --> 00:18:35.640
of study.

00:18:35.640 --> 00:18:39.580
Liberia is a country that's had
what we'll call relative peace

00:18:39.580 --> 00:18:45.640
