rice riots of 1980 [inaudible]

00:18:45.640 --> 00:18:47.600
in the governments of Samuel Doe --

00:18:47.600 --> 00:18:49.600
the military governments
of Samuel Doe.

00:18:49.600 --> 00:18:54.200
Which led to a decade of
crisis in that country.

00:18:54.200 --> 00:18:59.590 position:56%
And then, an insurgency that started
in 1989, of which the reports

00:18:59.590 --> 00:19:02.040
of the Liberian Truth and
Reconciliation Commission says --

00:19:02.040 --> 00:19:07.920
and I quote -- "Quickly degenerated
into a rebellion without a cause.

00:19:07.920 --> 00:19:11.470
At one point, a seven
cornered fight as represented

00:19:11.470 --> 00:19:14.030
by seven distinct warring factions,

00:19:14.030 --> 00:19:17.040
engaged in a full blown
fratricidal civil war."

00:19:17.040 --> 00:19:20.880
At the height of the
14-year civil war in Liberia,

00:19:20.880 --> 00:19:22.720
several hundred thousand
Liberians fled

00:19:22.720 --> 00:19:26.230
to neighboring countries
in a single year.

00:19:26.230 --> 00:19:31.200
It is estimated that in the cause
of the war, between 1989 and 2003,

00:19:31.200 --> 00:19:36.310
three quarters of the 3 million
strong Liberian population became

00:19:36.310 --> 00:19:38.960
either refugees or
internally displaced.

00:19:38.960 --> 00:19:40.260
And that's a very big number.

00:19:40.260 --> 00:19:45.240
It's also estimated by
the government of Liberia

00:19:45.240 --> 00:19:50.470
that an approximate 10%
of the population died

00:19:50.470 --> 00:19:52.460
in the cause of that war.

00:19:52.460 --> 00:19:57.090
By the end of the civil war in
2003, the country was in ruins.

00:19:57.090 --> 00:19:59.280
All critical infrastructures
were destroyed.

00:19:59.280 --> 00:20:01.180
The economy was in shambles

00:20:01.180 --> 00:20:04.230
with productive capacity
almost entirely depleted.

00:20:04.230 --> 00:20:08.140
Unemployment was estimated
to be over 80%.

00:20:08.140 --> 00:20:10.640
These are figures from
the Government of Liberia.

00:20:10.640 --> 00:20:14.960
And this was the dire situation
to which refugees began to return

00:20:14.960 --> 00:20:18.550
at the end of the war in 2003.

00:20:18.550 --> 00:20:23.510
It took from about 2003
to 2012 -- thereabout --

00:20:23.510 --> 00:20:26.290
for the majority of refugees
from neighboring countries

00:20:26.290 --> 00:20:31.910
to make their way back
to Liberia as returnees

00:20:31.910 --> 00:20:34.120
to their country of origin.

00:20:34.120 --> 00:20:36.980
Now, the comprehensive
peace accords that ended

00:20:36.980 --> 00:20:42.050
that war says something --
specifies that the national --

00:20:42.050 --> 00:20:46.560
and I'm quoting from the Accra
Comprehensive Peace Accord.

00:20:46.560 --> 00:20:50.870
It's ethical [inaudible]
Sections 1a to c.

00:20:50.870 --> 00:20:54.250
That the National Transitional
Government of Liberia,

00:20:54.250 --> 00:20:57.470
with the assistance of the
International Community,

00:20:57.470 --> 00:21:01.460
shall design and implement a
plan for the voluntary return

00:21:01.460 --> 00:21:04.480
and reintegration of
Liberian refugees

00:21:04.480 --> 00:21:07.050
and internally displaced
persons, including non-combatants,

00:21:07.050 --> 00:21:11.590
in accordance with international
conventions, norms, and practices.

00:21:11.590 --> 00:21:15.500
And I highlight this to show
that post-conflict order

00:21:15.500 --> 00:21:18.890
that was designed for Liberia,
intimately embraced the rule

00:21:18.890 --> 00:21:22.270
of international community, working
with the government of Liberia

00:21:22.270 --> 00:21:26.740
to construct a society that would
be conducive to the restoration

00:21:26.740 --> 00:21:28.590
of livelihood and dignity

00:21:28.590 --> 00:21:33.000
for displaced persons
and returning refugees.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:36.010
How the returnees have
come to Liberia as home.

00:21:36.010 --> 00:21:39.620
And whenever I used home in
this presentation, there is --

00:21:39.620 --> 00:21:45.050 position:56%
a double quotation mark around it to
indicate that it remains a concept

00:21:45.050 --> 00:21:47.740
that I personally struggle
with and that many

00:21:47.740 --> 00:21:50.190
of our respondents
also struggle with.

00:21:50.190 --> 00:21:55.960 position:56%
And do not agree on how the
returnees encounter Liberia as home.

00:21:55.960 --> 00:22:01.800
Majority of my respondents
in interviews indicated

00:22:01.800 --> 00:22:06.210
that they fled Liberia because
of fear -- fear for their lives,

00:22:06.210 --> 00:22:08.850
for their families,
for their safety.

00:22:08.850 --> 00:22:11.960
And, of course, the most
cited reason for returning

00:22:11.960 --> 00:22:15.260
to the country was the end of
the war and the opportunity

00:22:15.260 --> 00:22:17.800
to participate in elections.

00:22:17.800 --> 00:22:25.090
Many of them indicated that they
also wanted to return to Liberia

00:22:25.090 --> 00:22:27.780
for what we call "push" reasons.

00:22:27.780 --> 00:22:31.330
In other words, they felt pushed
out of the countries of exile

00:22:31.330 --> 00:22:36.150
for various reasons including
suffering or unbearable conditions.

00:22:36.150 --> 00:22:37.530
People being cruel to them.

00:22:37.530 --> 00:22:39.020
These are their own words.

00:22:39.020 --> 00:22:41.530
Idleness and lack of
work in the camps

00:22:41.530 --> 00:22:45.170
or because United Nations
High Commissioner

00:22:45.170 --> 00:22:47.390
for Refugees said they
should return.

00:22:47.390 --> 00:22:50.930
Or because they lost
family members in exile.

00:22:50.930 --> 00:22:52.230
Or because the options

00:22:52.230 --> 00:22:55.450
for resettlement was
not working for them.

00:22:55.450 --> 00:22:58.830
Apparently, the search for
home was partly occasioned

00:22:58.830 --> 00:23:04.160
by the returnees' experiences
in exile which were antithetical

00:23:04.160 --> 00:23:08.960
to their place of comfort
thereby propelling the refugees

00:23:08.960 --> 00:23:10.790
to desire a better place.

00:23:10.790 --> 00:23:14.220
A place where they could
recover a sense of belong,

00:23:14.220 --> 00:23:16.930
of worth, and of dignity.

00:23:18.040 --> 00:23:21.020
All the returnees I interviewed
refer to Liberia as home.

00:23:21.020 --> 00:23:23.180
At least once in the conversation.

00:23:23.180 --> 00:23:26.970
And some, several times
over and over again.

00:23:26.970 --> 00:23:31.280
However, the political, social, and
economic situations of the country

00:23:31.280 --> 00:23:33.600
in the post-conflict
period are the challenges

00:23:33.600 --> 00:23:37.940
of reintegration were daunting
for these newly returned refugees.

00:23:37.940 --> 00:23:42.950
I will examine now the way in
which reintegration is forged

00:23:42.950 --> 00:23:45.750
or constructed by various actors.

00:23:50.040 --> 00:23:51.890
Many returnees, as I said earlier,

00:23:51.890 --> 00:23:54.740
returned because wants
the feeling of home.

00:23:54.740 --> 00:23:57.040
And whenever that sense
of home is absent

00:23:57.040 --> 00:24:00.140
or expected socio-economic
dividends are not attained,

00:24:00.140 --> 00:24:02.330
reintegration becomes uncertain.

00:24:02.330 --> 00:24:07.120
Laura Hammond, who worked with
Ethiopian returnees opined

00:24:07.120 --> 00:24:10.690
that home is associated with
community and circumstance rather

00:24:10.690 --> 00:24:13.160
than with a fixed geographical
space.

00:24:13.160 --> 00:24:17.660
Liisa Malkki who studied Hutu
refugees in Tanzania posited

00:24:17.660 --> 00:24:20.350
that refugees identify
themselves based

00:24:20.350 --> 00:24:24.640 position:56%
on certain socio-personal identities
such as gender, ethnicity, and age.

00:24:24.640 --> 00:24:26.360
And these are the factors

00:24:26.360 --> 00:24:29.620
that eventually determines
one's connection to a place

00:24:29.620 --> 00:24:33.850
and eventually, one's reintegration
in the country of origin.

00:24:33.850 --> 00:24:38.290
What this authors affirm --
and by which I confirm --

00:24:38.290 --> 00:24:43.940
some of my observations is that
return to a geographical location

00:24:43.940 --> 00:24:47.740
of memory and nostalgia is
an insufficient condition

00:24:47.740 --> 00:24:50.290
for the reintegration of returnees.

00:24:50.290 --> 00:24:54.590 position:56%
Other realities of existence play
key roles in determining the ability

00:24:54.590 --> 00:24:57.920
of former refugees to
settle down and thrive.

00:24:59.550 --> 00:25:03.210
In the Liberian case on this study
from interviews with agency staff

00:25:03.210 --> 00:25:07.350
and from review of documents, we
identified a plethora of actors

00:25:07.350 --> 00:25:11.300
that were involved in the
reintegration of refugees

00:25:11.300 --> 00:25:13.550
and has shift the process
in significant ways.

00:25:13.550 --> 00:25:16.850
I group these into four: the
national - the governmental actors

00:25:16.850 --> 00:25:19.190
or agencies; international actors;

00:25:19.190 --> 00:25:21.910
community based actors;
and individuals.

00:25:21.910 --> 00:25:25.590
The most prominent of these was
the Liberian government itself.

00:25:25.590 --> 00:25:27.940
The chief government agency
with the responsibility

00:25:27.940 --> 00:25:32.060
for Liberian returnees was the
Liberian Refugee Repatriation

00:25:32.060 --> 00:25:33.830
and Resettlement Commission
-- LRRRC.

00:25:33.830 --> 00:25:39.220
We call it the L-triple
R-C, and it had offices

00:25:39.220 --> 00:25:42.030
in all the returnee
areas and was created

00:25:42.030 --> 00:25:44.520
by an act of parliament in 1993.

00:25:44.520 --> 00:25:49.690 position:56%
Its mandate covers refugees from all
over Liberia, as well as returnees

00:25:49.690 --> 00:25:52.520
to Liberia, as well as
internally displaced persons.

00:25:52.520 --> 00:25:56.330
Their main goal is to ensure
repatriation is safety and dignity.

00:25:56.330 --> 00:26:00.160
And so, they partner with UNHCR
and other agencies that work

00:26:00.160 --> 00:26:04.300
with bringing refugees
back to the country.

00:26:04.300 --> 00:26:08.600
And role of this government agency,
according to the program officer

00:26:08.600 --> 00:26:12.080
for repatriation, is to create
a conducive atmosphere free

00:26:12.080 --> 00:26:15.220
from harassment and other problems

00:26:15.220 --> 00:26:18.450
and to ensure repatriation
in safety and dignity.

00:26:18.450 --> 00:26:23.740
And they perform various
tasks towards this end.

00:26:23.740 --> 00:26:29.180 position:56%
Now, we know that the majority of
refugees -- we know this for a fact,

00:26:29.180 --> 00:26:36.050 position:56%
women and children -- and so we were
interested in finding the role of --

00:26:36.050 --> 00:26:40.410
looking for what aspect of
government is responsible

00:26:40.410 --> 00:26:43.560
for attending to their
needs as returnees.

00:26:43.560 --> 00:26:46.710
Now the Minister of Gender
and Development, we found,

00:26:46.710 --> 00:26:49.050
was playing an active role

00:26:49.050 --> 00:26:51.530
in charting the post-war
position of Liberian women.

00:26:51.530 --> 00:26:56.460
They convened a national gender
based violence task force

00:26:56.460 --> 00:27:00.620
that was a platform for interagency
coordination for all the agencies

00:27:00.620 --> 00:27:05.800
that work with Liberian women,
including women returnees.

00:27:05.800 --> 00:27:10.120
And this task force, we found --
I did attend some of the meetings

00:27:10.120 --> 00:27:14.930
of the task force -- had expended
a lot of efforts to produce,

00:27:14.930 --> 00:27:20.070 position:56%
for example, a simplified version of
Liberia's ground breaking rape law.

00:27:20.070 --> 00:27:24.230
And they also had created
a monthly reports and form

00:27:24.230 --> 00:27:27.280
for documenting cases of
gender based violence --

00:27:27.280 --> 00:27:29.510
GBV -- across the country.

00:27:29.510 --> 00:27:32.590
In other -- now the accents of
implementation of these kinds

00:27:32.590 --> 00:27:36.860
of policy instruments is a
separate matter by itself.

00:27:36.860 --> 00:27:41.630
The Ministry of Gender also
officially celebrates the United

00:27:41.630 --> 00:27:44.490
Nation's declared 16
days of activism

00:27:44.490 --> 00:27:47.040
against violence, against women.

00:27:47.040 --> 00:27:49.440
That's between November
25 and December 10,

00:27:49.440 --> 00:27:52.000
thereby linking Liberian
women's struggles

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:54.350
with global women's struggles.

00:27:54.350 --> 00:27:58.810
We found this GBV task
force replicated

00:27:58.810 --> 00:28:01.010
in other countries that I visited.

00:28:01.010 --> 00:28:03.300
I attended a meeting
again in Lofa County.

00:28:03.300 --> 00:28:06.940
I found that the efforts
that were being promoted

00:28:06.940 --> 00:28:10.460
in the capital were also
being promoted and replicated

00:28:10.460 --> 00:28:14.260
in the counties which
was indeed had need.

00:28:14.260 --> 00:28:17.430
Another agency that I find
relevant to our discussion

00:28:17.430 --> 00:28:21.830 position:56%
of the post-conflict context for
Liberian returnees is Liberia Agency

00:28:21.830 --> 00:28:23.680
for Community Empowerment.

00:28:23.680 --> 00:28:25.430
L-A-C-E. LACE.

00:28:25.430 --> 00:28:29.220
And this organization was
specifically born out of the need

00:28:29.220 --> 00:28:34.160
for funds for post-war
rehabilitation of infrastructure.

00:28:34.160 --> 00:28:37.670
In spite of the constraints
of external indebtedness

00:28:37.670 --> 00:28:40.840
that made this initially difficult
for the Liberian Government

00:28:40.840 --> 00:28:43.570
to benefit from the
World Bank's programs.

00:28:43.570 --> 00:28:48.210
According to government records,
the Liberian Government defaulted

00:28:48.210 --> 00:28:51.580
on its debts in the mid-1980s.

00:28:51.580 --> 00:28:57.550
And by 2006, external debts had
soared to 4.5 billion U.S. dollars.

00:28:57.550 --> 00:29:02.240
Which was equivalent of
800% of the country's GDP.

00:29:02.240 --> 00:29:05.970
And the equivalent
of 3000% of exports.

00:29:08.050 --> 00:29:12.310 position:56%
It was because of this that the LACE
was established in 2004 by an act

00:29:12.310 --> 00:29:15.600
of parliament to administer
a $6-billion grant

00:29:15.600 --> 00:29:17.570
from the World Bank.

00:29:17.570 --> 00:29:21.180
And the agencies mandates, in
the words of the program manager,

00:29:21.180 --> 00:29:25.700
was community driven development
through community empowerment.

00:29:25.700 --> 00:29:29.150 position:56%
And because these are the
communities that refugees return to,

00:29:29.150 --> 00:29:33.510
I was interested in
the activities of LACE.

00:29:33.510 --> 00:29:38.150
And one final government agency
I just mention, is the truth --

00:29:38.150 --> 00:29:40.840
I would say was the Truth
and Reconciliation Commission

00:29:40.840 --> 00:29:45.850
of Liberia, the TRC,
which the Chairperson said

00:29:45.850 --> 00:29:50.220
to me was created specifically

00:29:50.220 --> 00:29:55.100
to promote national healing
and national empathy.

00:29:55.100 --> 00:29:59.610
Because Truth, according to him, is
the [inaudible] of reconciliation.

00:29:59.610 --> 00:30:07.330 position:56%
We know that return to post-conflict
context includes the capacity

00:30:07.330 --> 00:30:10.600
of citizens to live
together in peace once again.

00:30:10.600 --> 00:30:14.550
And so, the work of the TRC was
one of those that we explored.

00:30:14.550 --> 00:30:18.080
International agencies, of course,
the most important was the UNHCR.

00:30:18.080 --> 00:30:21.610
Everywhere I went in Liberia,
the UNHCR was visible.

00:30:21.610 --> 00:30:24.490
And their activities could be seen.

00:30:24.490 --> 00:30:28.810
As a matter of fact,
the UNHCR seemed

00:30:28.810 --> 00:30:32.060
to be the most authoritative
structure of governance

00:30:32.060 --> 00:30:36.390
on the ground in many of
the counties that I visited.

00:30:36.390 --> 00:30:40.350
Even before organized repatriation,
before the government came to some

00:30:40.350 --> 00:30:44.880
of these places, the UNHCR was
there preparing those counties

00:30:44.880 --> 00:30:48.480
for the return of refugees
from neighboring countries.

00:30:48.480 --> 00:30:52.330
So, the agency was
engaged in several --

00:30:52.330 --> 00:30:55.370
not just reintegration activities
or repatriation activities,

00:30:55.370 --> 00:30:57.350
but some governance functions too.

00:30:57.350 --> 00:31:00.260
Providing health, education,
agriculture, shelter,

00:31:00.260 --> 00:31:02.950
and several other functions.

00:31:02.950 --> 00:31:06.790
The United Nations Mission
in Liberia was another agency

00:31:06.790 --> 00:31:10.120
that we engaged with
and saw the activities.

00:31:10.120 --> 00:31:13.040
And I want to mention here,
just one of the many NGOs

00:31:13.040 --> 00:31:15.730
that we found acting
also on the ground,

00:31:15.730 --> 00:31:17.630
the International Rescue Committee,

00:31:17.630 --> 00:31:22.450
which specifically had
extensive programs for women.

00:31:22.450 --> 00:31:26.390
Established women's centers,
women's department programs,

00:31:26.390 --> 00:31:30.590
women's resources [inaudible]
and did psycho-social counselling

00:31:30.590 --> 00:31:38.090
with women which was a very, very
rare activity amongst other NGOs.

00:31:38.090 --> 00:31:40.800
At the committee level,
we interviewed committee

00:31:40.800 --> 00:31:43.570
and religious leaders, youth
leaders, women leaders,

00:31:43.570 --> 00:31:46.140
but specifically, I'll
mention one here.

00:31:46.140 --> 00:31:48.600
One group here.

00:31:48.600 --> 00:31:52.800
The District Development
Committees which were created

00:31:52.800 --> 00:31:57.660
by the United Nations Development
Program, the UNDP, and the Ministry

00:31:57.660 --> 00:32:02.390
of Internal Affairs to bring power,
in quotes, to the grassroots.

00:32:02.390 --> 00:32:04.650
And their job was to
monitor projects carried

00:32:04.650 --> 00:32:08.650
out by various agencies, evaluate
and report on these projects

00:32:08.650 --> 00:32:12.620 position:56%
to ensure accountability, as well as
receive information from the people

00:32:12.620 --> 00:32:18.300 position:56%
in the communities about their
needs and channel these to the UNDP.

00:32:18.300 --> 00:32:22.850
Ultimately, however, reintegration,
however conceived, is personal.

00:32:22.850 --> 00:32:26.960
In other words, it is the returnee
refugee's participation in his

00:32:26.960 --> 00:32:28.580
or her own reintegration

00:32:28.580 --> 00:32:31.170
that determines the
outcome for each person.

00:32:31.170 --> 00:32:35.060
While local and international
agencies may expend efforts towards

00:32:35.060 --> 00:32:37.660
creating conducive
conditions in the resource,

00:32:37.660 --> 00:32:42.040
most exercise the prerogative
to return voluntarily

00:32:42.040 --> 00:32:45.580
to access reintegration program
and to achieve the full exercise

00:32:45.580 --> 00:32:49.390
of the rights and dignities
lost to them as exiles of war.

00:32:49.390 --> 00:32:56.150 position:56%
Now I'll quickly look at the global
-- how the global and the local meet

00:32:56.150 --> 00:32:58.920
in this process of forging
home before I conclude.

00:32:58.920 --> 00:33:02.050
I have tried to skip a lot of talks

00:33:02.050 --> 00:33:05.970
so that we can have
time to still discuss.

00:33:10.040 --> 00:33:13.060
Refugee experience has
shown that home cannot,

00:33:13.060 --> 00:33:16.180
and does not have exactly
the same dictionary meaning

00:33:16.180 --> 00:33:17.760
to returning refugees.

00:33:17.760 --> 00:33:21.790
One, nostalgia may invoke the
traditional expectation of home,

00:33:21.790 --> 00:33:25.740 position:56%
reintegration experiences are potent
for shifting these expectations

00:33:25.740 --> 00:33:29.690
and act towards or further
away from the ideal.

00:33:29.690 --> 00:33:34.600
Here, in this section, I'm going
to [inaudible] process of shaping.

00:33:34.600 --> 00:33:40.630
Perhaps the process of invasion
or imitation of the institutional,

00:33:40.630 --> 00:33:45.100
material, and ideational reference
of home in post-conflict Liberia

00:33:45.100 --> 00:33:49.060
by both local actors and
international agencies.

00:33:49.060 --> 00:33:54.360
The first point here is that the
very discourse on return, on home,

00:33:54.360 --> 00:33:57.870
reintegration, rights of
refugees, and the desirability

00:33:57.870 --> 00:34:04.620 position:56%
of repatriation, that very discourse
is shift by international norms,

00:34:04.620 --> 00:34:09.130
processes, actors, and regimes
that leave little or no room

00:34:09.130 --> 00:34:11.320
for initiative of the individual.

00:34:11.320 --> 00:34:14.150
And I give -- I explained this --

00:34:14.150 --> 00:34:16.860
when the human security framework
was popularized by the UNDP

00:34:16.860 --> 00:34:23.000
in the early 1990s, the UNHCR
defined reintegration in terms

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:28.000
of human security as the process
by which returnees achieve,

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:32.360
and I quote, "a progressively
greater degree of physical, social,

00:34:32.360 --> 00:34:35.220
legal, and material security."

00:34:35.220 --> 00:34:39.920
When the human security framework
came under critique by said actors,

00:34:39.920 --> 00:34:43.990
the UNHCR redefined reintegration
using human rights discourse

00:34:43.990 --> 00:34:45.530
as legisumation [phonetic].

00:34:45.530 --> 00:34:50.010
And so, reintegration -- by 2004,
came to be defined by the UNHCR

00:34:50.010 --> 00:34:53.820
as a process that should result in
the disappearance of differences

00:34:53.820 --> 00:34:59.400
in legal rights and duties between
returnees and their compatriots.

00:34:59.400 --> 00:35:03.090
And, of course, these frames are
basically imposed on the discourse

00:35:03.090 --> 00:35:07.600
on refugee reintegration as
refugees are rarely, if ever,

00:35:07.600 --> 00:35:09.950
involved in firm and
durable solutions

00:35:09.950 --> 00:35:12.300
at the conceptualization level.

00:35:12.300 --> 00:35:14.840
The overbearing role of
the UNHCR in this process

00:35:14.840 --> 00:35:16.760
of norming [phonetic] is
worthy of [inaudible].

00:35:16.760 --> 00:35:20.540
Many of our research participants
stated categorically that,

00:35:20.540 --> 00:35:24.730
while in the refugee camps,
the UNHCR was instrumental

00:35:24.730 --> 00:35:29.420
to painting the picture of a
desirable home in Liberia in order

00:35:29.420 --> 00:35:31.650
to encourage them to repatriate.

00:35:31.650 --> 00:35:33.850
In a fated dance, state actors

00:35:33.850 --> 00:35:38.860
in post-conflict situations
replicate this idea and insist

00:35:38.860 --> 00:35:42.270
on repatriation mainly
for political reasons.

00:35:42.270 --> 00:35:44.510
Because the success of
return and reintegration

00:35:44.510 --> 00:35:48.440
of refugees is deemed a powerful
endorsement of the [inaudible]

00:35:49.770 --> 00:35:55.810 position:56%
regime. So, the governments of these
newly post-conflict states then hand

00:35:55.810 --> 00:35:58.970
down this conception of the
desirability of these norms.

00:36:01.440 --> 00:36:04.450
Especially here with reference
to repatriation of refugees

00:36:04.450 --> 00:36:07.970 position:56%
through their legislatures --
meaning that they make relevant laws

00:36:07.970 --> 00:36:11.650
and thereby create institutions
through the implementing agencies

00:36:11.650 --> 00:36:14.710
of government, through
local governance structures

00:36:14.710 --> 00:36:18.480
which are questioningly perpetuated
these constructs of home.

00:36:18.480 --> 00:36:22.650
Together, these global and local
forces then weave the ideational

00:36:22.650 --> 00:36:24.260
context for return and [inaudible]

00:36:24.260 --> 00:36:29.840 position:56%
to take place forging what is
sometimes a false sense of security.

00:36:30.900 --> 00:36:35.100
It is obvious that these ideas need
to be purveyed by certain agents

00:36:35.100 --> 00:36:37.150
which in their function
and apply these norms

00:36:37.150 --> 00:36:39.100
and ideas and bring them to life.

00:36:39.100 --> 00:36:40.980 position:56%
A And this is the second point here.

00:36:40.980 --> 00:36:43.660
The very determination
of actors or agencies

00:36:43.660 --> 00:36:46.560
which eventually forge
the reintegration context

00:36:46.560 --> 00:36:50.500
for refugees is also jointly
achieved by international forces,

00:36:50.500 --> 00:36:52.850
national governments,
and local actors.

00:36:52.850 --> 00:36:54.920
And I give a few examples.

00:36:54.920 --> 00:36:58.440
It is a vote of the United
Nations Security Council

00:36:58.440 --> 00:37:00.890
that establishes a
peace keeping mission

00:37:00.890 --> 00:37:04.450
such as United Nations mission
in Liberia which became critical

00:37:04.450 --> 00:37:07.520
to reestablishing security
in that country.

00:37:07.520 --> 00:37:10.880
And establishing stability
and democratic governance.

00:37:10.880 --> 00:37:15.910 position:56%
The UNHCR -- which occupies a
unique position among UN agencies --

00:37:17.350 --> 00:37:18.650
Is another important one.

00:37:18.650 --> 00:37:22.510 position:56%
It is the executive committee of
the UNHCR that determines the extent

00:37:22.510 --> 00:37:27.200
of the organizations involvement
in specific areas during its scope

00:37:27.200 --> 00:37:28.840
and which, as politically

00:37:28.840 --> 00:37:32.050
and oppressionally
[phonetic] expedient...

00:37:32.050 --> 00:37:36.760
one refugee scholar says, and
I quote very clearly, well,

00:37:36.760 --> 00:37:41.300
very carefully, that successive
high commissioners quickly realize

00:37:41.300 --> 00:37:46.630
that in order to have any impact
on the world political arena,

00:37:46.630 --> 00:37:50.110
they have to use the power
of their expertise, ideas,

00:37:50.110 --> 00:37:52.070
strategies, and legitimacy.

00:37:52.070 --> 00:37:55.360
To author -- the information
and value context

00:37:55.360 --> 00:37:57.590
in which states made policy.

00:37:57.590 --> 00:38:03.090 position:56%
The office of the UNHCR has tried to
project refugee norms in to a world

00:38:03.090 --> 00:38:05.330
of politics dominated by states.

00:38:05.330 --> 00:38:08.200
For most of its history,
the office has acted

00:38:08.200 --> 00:38:12.120
as a teacher of refugee norms.

00:38:12.120 --> 00:38:15.630
UNHCR not only acted as the
transmitter of refugee norms

00:38:15.630 --> 00:38:19.420
but also socialize new states
to accept the promotion

00:38:19.420 --> 00:38:23.260
of refugee norms domestically
as part of the common members

00:38:23.260 --> 00:38:25.290
of the international community.

00:38:25.290 --> 00:38:29.350 position:56%
These decisions at that global level
are then replicated at national,

00:38:29.350 --> 00:38:31.250
community, and local levels.

00:38:31.250 --> 00:38:35.710
In the Liberian case on the study,
for example, the government set

00:38:35.710 --> 00:38:41.230
up its own refugee agency,
the LRRRC to parallel and work

00:38:41.230 --> 00:38:43.330
with the UNHCR's objectives.

00:38:43.330 --> 00:38:46.710
When the UNDP required
community structures to work,

00:38:46.710 --> 00:38:49.600
the government set up the
District Development Committees.

00:38:49.600 --> 00:38:52.740
When the World Bank needed a
credible agency outside the corrupt

00:38:52.740 --> 00:38:55.920
machineries of government
to administer new loans,

00:38:55.920 --> 00:38:58.340
then the government
also created the LACE --

00:38:58.340 --> 00:39:01.110
the Liberian Agency for
Community Empowerment.

00:39:01.110 --> 00:39:06.890
Those we see here -- a persistent,
concurrent, and concomitant machine

00:39:06.890 --> 00:39:10.510
of global intentions and actors
with local desires and agents

00:39:10.510 --> 00:39:14.330
to forge the reintegration
context for returning refugees.

00:39:14.330 --> 00:39:17.440
The third instance I'm
going to mention here --

00:39:17.440 --> 00:39:21.850 position:56%
that's the penultimate one -- is the
conjoining of local and global agent

00:39:21.850 --> 00:39:26.970
in constructing reintegration
concerns especially with respect

00:39:26.970 --> 00:39:31.260
to the determination of projects
of importance to be implemented.

00:39:31.260 --> 00:39:34.850
The data we have shows
that a lot of times,

00:39:34.850 --> 00:39:40.340
the local communities are invited
to participate in the activities

00:39:40.340 --> 00:39:43.880
of these various international
and government agencies

00:39:43.880 --> 00:39:47.950
by suggesting projects
to be implemented.

00:39:47.950 --> 00:39:51.200
But we found that a lot of
times -- in most cases --

00:39:51.200 --> 00:39:54.590
the role of these local agents
did not include envisioning

00:39:54.590 --> 00:39:56.890
and program design.

00:40:00.060 --> 00:40:03.040
The fourth and final dimension
I just want to mention here

00:40:03.040 --> 00:40:08.000
of this local and global
intersections

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:13.760
in the reintegration context is
a bit positive because we found,

00:40:13.760 --> 00:40:18.450
in almost every county
that I visited, that --

00:40:18.450 --> 00:40:22.450
we found specific instances
of global level actors working

00:40:22.450 --> 00:40:25.850
through international benedictions
and governments collaborator

00:40:25.850 --> 00:40:29.930
with local groups to provide
reintegration services.

00:40:29.930 --> 00:40:34.840
So, whereas, it was difficult
to include them in the selection

00:40:34.840 --> 00:40:36.910
of projects because those are --

00:40:36.910 --> 00:40:40.200
[inaudible] driven and
politically driven sometimes.

00:40:40.200 --> 00:40:45.570
The global meets the local in the
Liberian context most effectively

00:40:45.570 --> 00:40:49.340
and most positively in the
implementation of projects.

00:40:49.340 --> 00:40:53.190
And we found several
examples of certain projects.

00:40:53.190 --> 00:40:57.000
One of the most common that the
UNHCR used, not just in Liberia

00:40:57.000 --> 00:41:00.560
but around the world, were the
community empowerment projects.

00:41:00.560 --> 00:41:04.040
But I found one and I
wanted to just mention here,

00:41:04.040 --> 00:41:07.130
the Voinjama District Women
Organization for Peace

00:41:07.130 --> 00:41:12.510
and Development which was a
program in the Lofa county area

00:41:12.510 --> 00:41:15.390
of Liberia founded by the UNHCR --

00:41:15.390 --> 00:41:19.340
both managed by the women in
that committee themselves.

00:41:19.340 --> 00:41:22.750
And it was free for all
participants and they found this --

00:41:22.750 --> 00:41:27.060
the assessed that it was
useful for their reintegration.

00:41:27.060 --> 00:41:30.960
I will conclude at this time...

00:41:34.200 --> 00:41:38.300
My paper has explored intersections
between global and local agencies

00:41:38.300 --> 00:41:40.840
in constructing the
[inaudible] ideal of home

00:41:40.840 --> 00:41:44.010
for returning refugees to Liberia.

00:41:44.010 --> 00:41:46.800
International norms are
created and handed down.

00:41:46.800 --> 00:41:49.860
Various actors are created to
participate in the application

00:41:49.860 --> 00:41:53.680 position:56%
of these norms and deliberate action
is taken by global and local actors

00:41:53.680 --> 00:41:56.990
who collaborate on the
selection and implementation

00:41:56.990 --> 00:42:00.780
of reintegration projects.

00:42:01.910 --> 00:42:03.380
The outcome of these processes

00:42:03.380 --> 00:42:05.970
for the reintegration
of refugees is two-fold.

00:42:05.970 --> 00:42:10.540
Home becomes no more than a
fabrication for some and for some,

00:42:10.540 --> 00:42:12.730
it remains a goal to be attained.

00:42:12.730 --> 00:42:17.240
If home is a fabrication, a
product artificially constructed

00:42:17.240 --> 00:42:19.980
by the interflow of the
various ideas, norms,

00:42:19.980 --> 00:42:25.110
and actors both originating and
present in the country of return,

00:42:25.110 --> 00:42:28.380
that means that returnees must
work for their reintegration

00:42:28.380 --> 00:42:31.420 position:56%
by taking decided actions, decisions

00:42:31.420 --> 00:42:34.270
for creating the home
that they desire.

00:42:34.270 --> 00:42:37.740
If home is destination,

00:42:37.740 --> 00:42:42.250
then it means that returnees
themselves must strive

00:42:42.250 --> 00:42:46.180
for that ideal.

00:42:46.180 --> 00:42:48.900
That destination they
refer to as home.

00:42:48.900 --> 00:42:54.580 position:56%
Because the home they remember,
usually, with time blunted nostalgia

00:42:54.580 --> 00:42:57.540
from the pre-conflict
period no longer exists.

00:42:57.540 --> 00:43:01.660 position:56%
And the home they fled from during
the war, of course, was undesirable.

00:43:01.660 --> 00:43:02.960
And the home that they encounter

00:43:02.960 --> 00:43:05.730
when they return is
not really perfect.

00:43:05.730 --> 00:43:10.950
And so, these former exiles who are
stripped of options in most cases,

00:43:10.950 --> 00:43:12.900
must continue to forge
ahead steadily

00:43:12.900 --> 00:43:16.660 position:56%
but surely towards that destination.

00:43:16.660 --> 00:43:21.410
A place of comfort called home.

00:43:21.410 --> 00:43:26.760
If they must achieve
their ideals again

00:43:26.760 --> 00:43:34.380
because as Bill Bryson puts
it, "once you leave home,

00:43:34.380 --> 00:43:37.160
you can't go home again."

00:43:37.160 --> 00:43:40.720
And these implications
for the many refugee

00:43:40.720 --> 00:43:45.490
and returnee repatriation
context around the globe today.

00:43:45.490 --> 00:43:47.990
I want to thank everyone
for listening.

