anything about that.

00:52:45.430 --> 00:52:52.980
And that was one of the
concerns of refugees either --

00:52:52.980 --> 00:52:59.370
outside Liberia who were still
refugees in Nigeria a while back.

00:52:59.370 --> 00:53:02.990
And sometimes, there's not
much the government can do.

00:53:02.990 --> 00:53:06.840
In the case of Liberia, may of the
so-called enemies were, and are,

00:53:06.840 --> 00:53:12.780
holding powerful positions in
government, in their counties.

00:53:12.780 --> 00:53:17.920
And there's nothing these
refugees can do about that.

00:53:17.920 --> 00:53:20.290
It's either they refuse to
return or they just submit --

00:53:20.290 --> 00:53:23.550
as some just said to me in
Liberia, they are still afraid,

00:53:23.550 --> 00:53:24.850
but where else can they go?

00:53:24.850 --> 00:53:26.150
They lack choices.

00:53:26.150 --> 00:53:28.680
And many did mention that other
solutions such as integrations --

00:53:28.680 --> 00:53:29.980
local integration elsewhere --

00:53:29.980 --> 00:53:32.920
or resettlement were
not available to them.

00:53:32.920 --> 00:53:34.440
So, returning to Liberia was
because they had no choice.

00:53:34.440 --> 00:53:35.910
So, in that context, the
government -- as I said, usually,

00:53:35.910 --> 00:53:37.950 position:56%
eventually develops capacity to deal
with the harder psychosocial aspects

00:53:37.950 --> 00:53:39.250
of return, including
safety and dignity.

00:53:39.250 --> 00:53:40.550
And the restoration of rights
to people across the land.

00:53:40.550 --> 00:53:42.330
But in the immediate context, which
I saw, it was extremely difficult.

00:53:42.330 --> 00:53:43.630
The international agencies,
I would say,

00:53:43.630 --> 00:53:44.930
especially in the Liberian
context, were doing a great job.

00:53:44.930 --> 00:53:46.230
The UN mission in Liberia
was everywhere.

00:53:46.230 --> 00:53:47.530
The UNHCR, like I said,
was everywhere.

00:53:47.530 --> 00:53:48.850
Where the government was
absent, they were present.

00:53:48.850 --> 00:53:52.900
But again, their mandates are
quite specific which, again,

00:53:52.900 --> 00:53:57.430 position:56%
means that there isn't much they can
do but their presence seemed to --

00:53:57.430 --> 00:54:02.810
in many instances, make
the returnees feel a bit,

00:54:02.810 --> 00:54:04.350
like, they were home.

00:54:04.350 --> 00:54:08.170
And they also expressed exactly
the same worry that you expressed.

00:54:08.170 --> 00:54:10.750
When the [inaudible] of
the UN mission Liberia --

00:54:10.750 --> 00:54:12.820
when it leaves, what's
going to happen to us?

00:54:12.820 --> 00:54:14.980
Many of them said this to me.

00:54:14.980 --> 00:54:17.670
Really. And there's
nothing anyone can say

00:54:17.670 --> 00:54:20.180
because the mission will leave.

00:54:20.180 --> 00:54:22.770
They will have to grapple
with their own governments.

00:54:23.800 --> 00:54:25.600
&gt;&gt; Another question over here.

00:54:25.600 --> 00:54:52.560
[Inaudible comment]

00:54:52.560 --> 00:54:53.860
&gt;&gt; Olajumoke Yacob-Haliso:
Absolutely.

00:54:53.860 --> 00:54:58.430
&gt;&gt; For instance, if you left
your country because of war,

00:54:58.430 --> 00:55:04.510 position:56%
and you're a refugee in another
country, and you're going back to --

00:55:04.510 --> 00:56:57.040
[Inaudible comment]

00:56:57.040 --> 00:56:58.620
&gt;&gt; Olajumoke Yacob-Haliso:
Thank you very much for that.

00:56:58.620 --> 00:57:00.720
I won't disagree with you.

00:57:00.720 --> 00:57:09.360
And one of the -- I think, I
could say one basic fact is

00:57:09.360 --> 00:57:12.990
that when refugees return
to a post-conflict context,

00:57:12.990 --> 00:57:20.110
this situation in the country of
origin, at first, is usually worse

00:57:20.110 --> 00:57:23.500
than the situation in the refugee
camps where they're coming from.

00:57:23.500 --> 00:57:27.290
At least, [inaudible] the
country begins to recover.

00:57:27.290 --> 00:57:31.840
What I found in Liberia is not
just because there were no economic

00:57:31.840 --> 00:57:35.780
and order opportunities, it
was instead the expectations

00:57:35.780 --> 00:57:40.140
of the refugees were too high
for a post-conflict context.

00:57:40.140 --> 00:57:44.770
And so, they returned and they were
highly disappointed about the fact

00:57:44.770 --> 00:57:47.310
that there were no
jobs, there were no --

00:57:47.310 --> 00:57:48.960
even the queues the [inaudible].

00:57:48.960 --> 00:57:50.980
There were not markets
for those queues.

00:57:50.980 --> 00:57:53.230
And so many such problems.

00:57:53.230 --> 00:57:56.530
So, I do understand.

00:57:56.530 --> 00:58:00.780
I just see [inaudible]
speaking about what --

00:58:00.780 --> 00:58:08.540
I also think that beyond appealing
to the international community,

00:58:08.540 --> 00:58:13.860 position:56%
the individuals, like I said in my
paper, as well as the communities --

00:58:13.860 --> 00:58:19.190
where they came together, they
were able to achieve some things.

00:58:19.190 --> 00:58:22.950
If there were more instances of
their coming together to articulate

00:58:22.950 --> 00:58:28.290
and find solutions, there would
have been better prospects

00:58:28.290 --> 00:58:29.590
of reintegration.

00:58:29.590 --> 00:58:33.810
But what we found instead was
a predisposition, in some case,

00:58:33.810 --> 00:58:37.580
to what I would call
"Aids dependence"

00:58:37.580 --> 00:58:40.220
and which has negative
consequences too.

00:58:40.220 --> 00:58:42.590
Just to give you another
side of that.

00:58:42.590 --> 00:58:44.390
Thank you.

00:58:44.390 --> 00:59:13.280
[Inaudible comment]

00:59:13.280 --> 00:59:15.230
Well, thank you very much.

00:59:15.230 --> 00:59:17.290
There are studies.

00:59:17.290 --> 00:59:19.850
But frankly speaking,
one of the justifications

00:59:19.850 --> 00:59:23.970
for my research has been that there
are very few in-depth case studies

00:59:23.970 --> 00:59:27.800
that show what's happening in a
particular country over the years

00:59:27.800 --> 00:59:30.550
which is what, I think,
I'm trying to do really.

00:59:30.550 --> 00:59:31.900
Following this particular case

00:59:31.900 --> 00:59:35.230
since I started following
in 2006 until now.

00:59:35.230 --> 00:59:38.870
And for Liberia, for instance,
I found just one other study.

00:59:38.870 --> 00:59:42.960
A 2011 study that tried
to also look at some

00:59:42.960 --> 00:59:44.260
of the issues that I looked at.

00:59:44.260 --> 00:59:46.390
Not many. And I found for, maybe,

00:59:46.390 --> 00:59:49.080
Angola and a few other
countries -- Columbia.

00:59:49.080 --> 00:59:53.050
A few other countries scattered
there but while there is a lot

00:59:53.050 --> 00:59:57.150
of work on refugee issues by
scholars around the world,

00:59:57.150 --> 01:00:03.210
I think we need more of an in-depth
look at each country's context

01:00:03.210 --> 01:00:06.560
because in many instances,
context is everything

01:00:06.560 --> 01:00:10.620
and not just the larger debates
that other scholars engage with.

01:00:10.620 --> 01:00:14.400
So, I would join you in saying
that we need to know more.

01:00:14.400 --> 01:00:17.810
The UNHCR itself, when I spoke with
expats that [inaudible] with us,

01:00:17.810 --> 01:00:23.230 position:56%
of course, through its own internal
processes tries to track the results

01:00:23.230 --> 01:00:26.160
of what they are doing
systematically.

01:00:26.160 --> 01:00:29.130
And because of that, I have
actually come to believe

01:00:29.130 --> 01:00:32.070
that it's probably one of
the most dynamic UN agency

01:00:32.070 --> 01:00:37.010
because it's more able to
adapt and change quickly

01:00:37.010 --> 01:00:41.530
to emergent situations in its
activities around the world.

01:00:41.530 --> 01:00:43.740
And, that's all.

